<HEADLINE>
<P>
WATER SUPPLY AND TRASH DISPOSAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I applaud your recent editorials "Dangerous Decision" (Oct. 5) and "Not the 
Right Spot to Begin With" (Sept. 30). I, too, agree that the expansion of the 
Azusa landfill is a dangerous decision in the wrong spot. In fact, I was 
startled by the State Water Resources Control Board's decision to support the 
expansion of the Azusa Western Landfill. 
</P>
<P>
Is the board not aware that Environmental Protection Agency has designated the 
San Gabriel ground-water contamination problem as the worst in the Western 
United States? It has been over 10 years since EPA detected this contamination 
and yet every day the residents of the San Gabriel Valley wonder if their 
drinking water is safe -- and how long it will remain so. Clearly, to build a 
landfill in the area would only contribute to the polluting of this aquifer. 
</P>
<P>
The State Water Resources Control Board members seemed so impressed by the 
presence of William Ruckelshaus (former EPA administrator) that they failed to 
see past the economic interests of his company, Browning-Ferris Industries 
(BFI). May I remind them that BFI is a company interested in making a profit. 
</P>
<P>
The San Gabriel ground-water basin provides 90% of the water supply for 1 
million people. If this aquifer is lost, where will these people obtain their 
water? The Metropolitan Water District is overburdened. Besides, this is an 
impractical and unnecessary alternative. 
</P>
<P>
As chairman of the Environment and Labor Subcommittee of the House Small 
Business Committee, I have come to realize that the ground-water contamination 
problems in the San Gabriel Valley have been brought on by years of neglect, as 
well as by willful actions by responsible parties. We have a duty to stop that 
neglect as well as to find those responsible for the dumping. Preventing the 
expansion of the Azusa landfill would help to stop the neglect. 
</P>
<P>
Like the MWD and the San Gabriel Valley Watermaster, I am thoroughly convinced 
that the expansion of the dump poses an unnecessary risk for further 
contamination. 
</P>
<P>
I fully anticipate that the watermaster and other interested parties will file 
a petition to allow the court to intercede in this matter. It is vitally 
important to San Gabriel Valley residents that they succeed. 
</P>
<P>
REP. ESTEBAN E. TORRES 
</P>
<P>
D-La Puente 
</P>
</TEXT>
