<HEADLINE>
<P>
STEEL FABRICATORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Esther McCoy's article "Los Angeles Case-Study Houses" (Opinion, Oct. 8) 
revived memories by this retired steel fabricator. Houlberg Iron performed 
several such houses, the most notable being Craig Ellwood's "Case Study House 
Number One," on Schuyler Road in Beverly Hills (circa 1952). P.B. Philbrick was 
the general contractor and proclaimed he only used $200 worth of wood on the 
entire structure, and that was the forming material for the concrete floor and 
foundation! 
</P>
<P>
Ellwood was a perfectionist who demanded that all welds be ground smooth, and 
hand-filed mitered corner joints were the rule. This was Houlberg Iron's first 
such project. I also recall examining the drawings of the late A. Ouincy Jones' 
"Below Grade" design (mentioned in McCoy's article) in his offices in West Los 
Angeles and was excited by the sheer simplicity of lightweight steel 
construction carrying the design to clean-cut perfection. 
</P>
<P>
J. PETER HOULBERG 
</P>
<P>
Montecito 
</P>
</TEXT>
