<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIMITING LENGTHY CRIMINAL TRIALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The column "When Justice Runs Out of Gas" (Op-Ed Page, Oct. 23) contains both 
dangerous thinking and naivete which is surprising from an attorney such as 
Royal Oakes. 
</P>
<P>
Megatrials are anomalies which happen only rarely. However, in a system of 
justice as large as the one in Los Angeles, the overlapping of them will occur 
from time to time. Thus, the Richard Ramirez (Night Stalker) and McMartin 
Pre-school trials took place concurrently. These types of unusual occurrences 
should be viewed as just that and not as a reason to change a system of justice 
which has, generally speaking, worked wonderfully well for 200 years in this 
country and for much longer than that in Great Britain. 
</P>
<P>
Oakes seems to attempt to put the blame for lengthy criminal cases on the 
defense, implying that lengthy voir dire is conducted only by defendants and 
directly stating that the defense uses unscrupulous tactics to lengthen trials. 
He also states that trial courts are so worried about having "perfect" trials 
that every whim of a defense lawyer to delay the trial is indulged. Courts of 
appeal have not and are not reversing convictions for minor errors committed by 
trial courts. 
</P>
<P>
The real reason for megatrials is that prosecutors often file every possible 
crime rather than attempting to limit the trial and do a second trial if 
necessary. With the sentencing scheme in California, it is unnecessary to 
charge 50-100 counts of child molestation as a conviction on 15 counts would 
suffice for a prison sentence from which the defendant would never be released. 
</P>
<P>
There is no need to reform a system which has worked wonderfully for 200 years 
merely because two or three unusual cases last a long time. 
</P>
<P>
ANDREW E. RUBIN 
</P>
<P>
Santa Monica 
</P>
</TEXT>
