<P>
Food; Part H; Page 32; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1482 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOOD AND COMMON SENSE: REDUCING FAT INTAKE A CONFUSING ISSUE, BUT GUIDELINES 
CAN HELP CUT USE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JEAN MAYER and JEANNE GOLDBERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Why is it," a health-conscious friend complained recently, "that you 
nutritionists are always making it more complicated to choose a healthy diet?" 
</P>
<P>
His lament referred to selecting fats for cooking and table spreads. For the 
past several years, he had paid close attention to reports on TV and radio and 
in newspapers chronicling research findings on how different types of fat 
affect serum cholesterol. The payoff, he observed wistfully, is that he feels 
confused about exactly what he should be doing. 
</P>
<P>
He's not alone. Experts agree that reducing saturated fat is the most critical 
step in modifying fat intake to lower serum cholesterol. Yet the role of 
unsaturated fat, and the mix of polyunsaturated and monounsaturated fats we 
should consume, is far less clear. For such a complex question, it will take 
years of study, not the findings of any single project, to reach an answer. 
</P>
<P>
The other confusing factor in fat selection is the proliferation of butter 
alternatives and the advertising that accompanies them, tapping into some piece 
of the message for a healthy heart. 
</P>
<P>
Despite the confusion, we have to make decisions at the grocery store, in the 
kitchen, and all other places where we buy, prepare and eat food throughout the 
day. Luckily, there are some simple guidelines recommended to ease the process. 
</P>
<P>
Start by assuming you could use less fat in your diet. Although consumption has 
been dropping, the typical American gets considerably more fat than the current 
recommendation of 30% of total calories. The best approach to trimming fat is 
simply to eat lean: Choose low-fat or skim-milk dairy products, buy lean cuts 
of meat and eat smaller servings, use more chicken and fish, cook with a 
minimum of fat and use it sparingly at the table. 
</P>
<P>
For many people, this strategy might be all that's needed to reach the target 
of 30% of total calories, as well as to create a diet where no more than 10% of 
the fat is saturated, with the rest evenly split between monounsaturates and 
polyunsaturates. At nine calories per gram, fat is the most calorie-dense of 
the energy nutrients, compared to four per gram for either carbohydrate or 
protein. Thus, cutting back on fat might also mean you'll shed extra pounds. 
</P>
<P>
If step one is to take a well-sharpened paring knife to the fat -- especially 
saturated -- in your diet, step two is to make informed choices about those 
fats you do buy for cooking and table spreads. Where oils are concerned, you 
can choose according to usage. 
</P>
<P>
For sauteing, take one of the many flavorless oils available. For salad 
dressings or dishes with a Mediterranean flavor, olive oil makes the zestiest 
choice. It should be used sparingly, so the fruitier the better. And in many 
Oriental dishes, peanut oil -- like olive, rich in monounsaturates and also 
carrying a distinctive flavor -- might be your pick. Again, a little goes a 
long way. 
</P>
<P>
So far, so good. When you hit the dairy case, however, you may feel lost in a 
jungle of products. Bear in mind this generalization: A tablespoon of regular, 
stick margarine, 80% fat and 20% water by weight, is calorically comparable to 
butter, providing 100 calories per tablespoon. 
</P>
<P>
Checking at the market, we found that all but three stick margarines provided 
labeling information. All except one contained two grams of saturated fat per 
tablespoon and one to three grams of polyunsaturated fat. Curiously, all but 
one manufacturer used a tablespoon as the serving size. This one exception used 
a teaspoon, which contained a gram of saturated fat. Multiply that by the three 
teaspoons to a tablespoon and you'll find the product more highly saturated 
than other brands. 
</P>
<P>
Of the three unlabeled margarines, two were made from partially hydrogenated 
vegetable oil, and it's unknown how saturated they are. The label on the third 
states that it "contains liquid corn oil," but again, we don't know whether 
it's hydrogenated and therefore more saturated. Among tub margarines, the one 
containing the most saturated fat used a teaspoon rather than a tablespoon as 
the portion of choice, thereby misleading the unwary consumer. 
</P>
<P>
What happens when these margarines are modified by whipping in water? Calories 
are reduced, but how much varies by brand. Consumers can make their selection 
both on taste and on desire to cut calories. Clearly, there's no getting around 
not reading the labels. 
</P>
<P>
Finally, there is a line of products whose appeal is unabashedly based on being 
a butter taste-alike. It may or may not achieve that objective. But, not 
surprisingly, the addition of butter boosts its quota of saturated fat. In 
making comparisons between this and other margarines, always remember to check 
for portion size. Otherwise, you may be getting more saturated fat than you 
bargained for. 
</P>
<P>
Not All Shellfish Have Excessive Cholesterol 
</P>
<P>
Question: I was sure I'd read in your column that most shellfish are no richer 
in cholesterol than lean meat or chicken. The other night I dined with a friend 
who says he knows all about the ins and outs of a cholesterol-lowering diet. He 
passed up scallops because, he said, they are a potent source of cholesterol. I 
thought he was wrong, but he was adamant. Who's right? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: You are. Assuming that the scallops weren't prepared with a lot of oil 
or margarine and weren't afloat in either melted butter or a rich cream sauce, 
they are not only low in cholesterol but also low in both fat and saturated 
fat. The scallops themselves, before any fat is added, contain less than a gram 
of fat and just 95 calories. 
</P>
<P>
To spare your friend's feelings, you can explain that his confusion is 
understandable. The problem is that at the time a link between dietary factors 
and serum cholesterol was first established, laboratory methods for analysis of 
dietary cholesterol were relatively primitive compared to today's fine-tuning. 
As a result, other compounds, which are chemically similar, were measured as 
cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
This error inflated the early values for shellfish. Although the mistake was 
later rectified, old learning has died a slow death. Many people, such as your 
dining companion, cling like limpets to the belief that shellfish are all rich 
in cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
In truth, many shellfish contain little. For example, three ounces of clams, 
mussels, oysters or scallops provide between 30 and 50 milligrams. That amount 
is considerably less than the 80 milligrams you would get from the same portion 
of veal, beef or chicken. 
</P>
<P>
The same amount of lobster contains somewhat more, about 90 milligrams. How 
much there is in shrimp depends on species, anywhere from as little as 60 
milligrams in Japanese prawns to three times that amount in the white Atlantic 
varieties. Squid, a mollusk most people do not recognize as such, contains 180 
milligrams of cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I know that ground beef does not keep as well as whole cuts, but I haven't 
the foggiest notion why. Can you enlighten me? 
</P>
<P>
A: There are two reasons why ground beef deteriorates more readily than a roast 
or even chunks cut for stew. For one thing, ground beef is often made from 
trimmings, so it has been handled more than larger pieces of meat. The handling 
process increases exposure to bacteria. For another, grinding the meat greatly 
multiplies the exposed surface area. That exposed area is an open playing field 
for bacteria naturally present in the environment. While these organisms are 
not harmful, they can cause a breakdown in quality, and even spoilage, if 
handled improperly. 
</P>
<P>
Because ground meat deteriorates so quickly, it should be held in the 
refrigerator for no more than a couple of days. If you don't get a chance to 
use it up within that time, you have several choices. One is to brown the meat 
well and use it in a cooked dish such as spaghetti sauce or chili, which can be 
eaten within a few days. 
</P>
<P>
Alternatively, it should be frozen. If you do choose to freeze it, remember 
that the best way to thaw it is in the refrigerator. Thawing meat on the 
counter is not recommended. That method allows the outer layer to warm to a 
temperature where bacteria thrive, while the inside remains solid. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I was preparing a batch of corn muffins when my mother offered to "help." 
She had never used corn meal before and when she opened a new box she wailed in 
dismay at the black specks inside. I assured her that it was perfectly fine and 
that those specks were always present in corn meal. She was dissatisfied with 
my answer. Can you tell my mother that I know what I'm talking about? 
</P>
<P>
A: Those black specks are indeed a natural part of the corn kernel. Corn 
kernels, like other grains, have three basic parts: the bran (or outer husk), 
the germ and the endosperm. These black specks, called the "hilar layer," are 
found at the base of the germ and connect it to the rest of the kernel. During 
milling, the hilar layer remains with the endosperm, and shows up as the dark 
specks you describe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA110289-0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 128782 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 2, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Food; Part H; Page 33; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
588 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE KITCHEN CABINET: TWO NEW CORDLESS IRONS OFFER MORE FLEXIBILITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MINNIE BERNARDINO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cordless irons have returned to the limelight after an unsuccessful spark some 
years ago. The initial reaction from consumers was good -- a dream come true 
for many ironers who wanted that cord out of the way of the iron. The cords 
disappeared indeed but the wrinkles didn't. Returns were heavy and users 
complained of the following: the units didn't produce enough heat or enough 
steam, and some were even dripping. 
</P>
<P>
Because the cordless mode is so convenient and fast when ironing lightweight 
articles or for maneuvering easily and quickly around tablecloths, sheets, 
silks, curtains or awkward pleats, the idea didn't die. Two new cordless irons 
have just been unveiled and could be the solution to the pressing problems of 
the first products. There's Tefal Freeline 50 ($99.99) from France and 
Rowenta's Mode 2 (CS-01) Cord/Cordless Iron ($110) from West Germany. 
</P>
<P>
Both products are now hot items in Europe and are expected to pick up more 
sales volume in the year to come. Rowenta is playing the safe game by adding 
the corded adaptability in their Mode 2. (To iron with the cord, you can easily 
attach the adapter with a cord to the iron by unlocking it from the charging 
base.) 
</P>
<P>
Because of this dual flexibility, the iron was much better received than the 
single cordless, gaining consumer trust, according to Paul Pofcher, Rowenta's 
general manager. "Sometimes you need the power of a cord iron when ironing 
denims and linens," he explained, "the technology of a continuous high ironing 
power does not exist." 
</P>
<P>
A cordless iron undoubtedly picks up heat from a charging corded base. After 
closely examining ironing habits, Rowenta's study revealed that people iron for 
only seven to 15 seconds before adjusting the material being ironed. The 
company designed an iron and base that allows recharging to an ideal ironing 
temperature. 
</P>
<P>
Its 1200 wattage promises greater heat and steam while its increased use of 
metal mass (copper and chromium shield plus the iron's all metal body) makes 
for better heat retention. Another important design feature is the angled base 
on which the iron rests. 
</P>
<P>
"One of the most stressful part of ironing is when you lift and set back the 
iron flat on its heel," Pofcher said. "our unit slides back on its angled base 
in a natural motion." In other words it eliminates the need to continuously 
wrench wrists backward to rest the iron. 
</P>
<P>
Other advantages in this ironing system include a transparent water tank that's 
removable, and capacity for two steam power levels and a fine mist spray. 
</P>
<P>
And then there's Tefal, favored by many consumers for its smooth gliding 
soleplate, powerful steam and water spray plus self-cleaning feature. Tefal's 
sleek-looking cordless version has all these features plus more. The 1500-watt 
Freeline 50 retains heat for three minutes and recharges quickly when set back 
on its flat corded base, which has a hidden cord storage. It also has a 
removable anti-clogging valve and a safety thermal cut-off, meaning you don't 
need to worry if you leave the iron on -- it will shut off automatically. 
</P>
<P>
Tefal's Durilium soleplate has a 10-year warranty. The ultra-smooth plate has 
been tested to glide over zippers without scratching its surface. The test also 
proved that the force required to handle an iron with this plate was 
considerably less than with alternative materials. 
</P>
<P>
 The Rowenta Mode 2 Cord/Cordless Iron is available at Bullock's, Buffum's and 
Robinson's. 
</P>
<P>
 The Tefal Freeline 50 Iron will be available mid-November at Bullock's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Rowenta Mode 2 iron offers flexibility of a dual cordless and corded 
system. Charging base is angled for easy iron lifting and resting. ; Photo, 
Freeline 50 iron features the same Tefal iron with popular ultraglide soleplate 
plus the added convenience and freedom of a cordless unit. MICHAEL EDWARDS / 
Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
