<P>
4.4 AFTERSHOCK RATTLES BAY AREA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An aftershock of the devastating Oct. 17 earthquake jolted Northern California 
from San Francisco Bay to Watsonville. The magnitude 4.4 aftershock was felt in 
San Francisco, Santa Cruz and Watsonville. There were no immediate reports of 
damage or injuries. "It rattled pretty good at first and then kept on kind of 
rolling. You could feel the foundation swaying," said Watsonville resident Ani 
LeRitz-Murphy. "It's been the second longest one we've had since the big 
quake." The aftershock at 9:50 p.m. Wednesday was centered slightly north of 
the epicenter of the magnitude 7.1 main temblor, according to the U.S. 
Geological Survey in Menlo Park. Of the thousands of aftershocks, 84 have 
measured at least magnitude 3.0, and 21 registered magnitude 4.0 or greater. 
The strongest was 5.2, just 37 minutes after the initial jolt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
