<P>
LOCAL; 
</P>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA FAMILY FLEES FIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A family escaped unharmed from their home in Santa Clarita this morning as 
flames swept through it, the Los Angeles County Fire Department reported. 
</P>
<P>
The fire in the home in the 24600 block of Arcadia Street was reported at 1:20 
a.m., dispatcher Stan Pearson said. Four members of a family living in the home 
were awakened and escaped. 
</P>
<P>
Marlene Morris said she was awakened by an explosion, possibly from an oxygen 
bottle that was stored in the garage. She woke her husband, Don, and two 
teen-age sons, including one whose leg was in a cast, and fled from the 
smoke-filled home. She said she burned her feet running across hot embers that 
had fallen in the house. 
</P>
<P>
The fire caused an estimated $120,000 damage and took firefighters about 15 
minutes to extinguish. Cause of the blaze is under investigation, Pearson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
