<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
WANG REPORTED SET TO IDLE 2,500 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LOWELL, Mass. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang Laboratories Inc., which recently ousted the founder's son as the 
company's president, plans to lay off another 2,500 employees, or 10% of the 
work force, a published report said today. 
</P>
<P>
The Boston Globe, citing a source close to the computer manufacturer, said the 
cuts, which Wang plans to announce next week, are part of a restructuring under 
new President Richard W. Miller. 
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Wang, which had losses of nearly $425 million in the fiscal 
year that ended June 30, declined to confirm or deny the reported layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
Miller came to Wang in August, replacing former President Frederick Wang, the 
son of company founder and Chairman An Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
