<HEADLINE>
<P>
NOT CHANGING STYLE, BANNED DRIVER SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ADELAIDE, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
emotional Ayrton Senna vowed today that a six-month ban hanging over his head 
would not affect his driving style in Sunday's Australian Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
Senna, who appeared close to tears a number of times during a press conference 
today, was responding to the $100,000 fine and six-month suspension handed up 
by the International Automobile Federation on Tuesday. The federation said 
Senna had endangered other drivers on several occasions this season but 
withheld implementation of the suspension for six months. The panel also upheld 
Senna's disqualification from the Japanese Grand Prix on Oct. 22. 
</P>
<P>
Senna, 29, said he will not moderate his aggression. "I'll drive the way I have 
driven all my career," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
